entry.title: [line-clamp] Make it possible to hide for paint non-table-cell boxes
entry.content:
`PhysicalFragment`s can be marked as hidden for paint, which makes

them invisible to paint regardless of `visibility` and other CSS

properties.



However, this is currently only used for hiding cells in a collapsed

table column, and while this can be set from `FragmentBuilder`, there

is no way to automatically set it from a constraint space. While there

is a `ConstraintSpace::IsTableCellHiddenForPaint`, besides being

specific to table cells and not generally applicable, it does not

automatically make fragments built from it hidden for paint.



Since line-clamp needs to be able to hide arbitrary boxes from paint,

this change changes the `ConstraintSpace` method to be a generic

`IsHiddenForPaint`, and makes the `FragmentBuilder` field default to

the constraint space's value.



This patch only refactors existing code and has no user-visible

effects.

This CL revises the sandbox + same-origin variation in the test

grandparent_location_aboutsrcdoc.sub.window.js to avoid a

entry.title: Make FrameSinkVideoCapturer supports RGBA with NativeTexture
entry.content:
Currently FrameSinkVideoCapturer only supports NV12 with

NativeTexture, I added format support for related codes and make it

also possible for RGBA.

Firstly, it is reasonable RenderableGpuMemoryBufferVideoFramePool

supports different formats, currently it is nailed to NV12 and cannot be

easily ported to other formats in future.

Also, with this change, the CEF OSR function can use shared GPU textures

to accelerate the paint. This function means greatly to CEF developers,

and I think it is better to make it goes into upstream Chromium instead

of a big patch. The Electron also wanted this for a long time. The OBS

also wanted this feature and they are stuck on M103 for a long time,

which might introduce possible security concerns.



https://bitbucket.org/chromiumembedded/cef/pull-requests/285

https://magpcss.org/ceforum/viewtopic.php?t=19404

https://github.com/electron/electron/issues/16961



Changes:



1. RenderableGpuMemoryBufferVideoFramePool supports multiple formats,

FrameSinkVideoCaptureImpl supports capturing RGBA use GMB mode,

VideoFramePool supports format-aware (GMB) and format-unaware

(SharedMemory) mode.

2. RenderableGpuMemoryBufferVideoFramePool use NV12 as default pixel

format to provide compability

3. DXGI GMB Factory supports BGRA_8888 texture

4. FrameSinkVideoCapturerImpl::DidCopyFrame supports GMB RGBA

5. Respect buffer_format_preference_ to recreate frame_pool_ when

FrameSinkVideoCapturerImpl::Start

6. FrameSinkVideoCaptureImpl use new GpuMemoryBufferVideoFramePool

7. Add test to `mojom::BufferFormatPreference::kPreferGpuMemoryBuffer + media::PIXEL_FORMAT_ARGB`

entry.title: Add test support classes for data migration.
entry.content:
These will be used in upcoming unit tests, and possibly integration

tests. There are essentially 4 layers at play:

DataMigration -> NearbyConnections (Chromium) -> NearbyConnections (Core) -> I/O (Platform)



Ideally, we would take the real code path for all of this in tests and

only fake the I/O layer. This is difficult to set up, especially in

unit tests. So the next best thing is to fake the "Core" layer. That

way, at least the middle "NearbyConnections (Chromium)" layer is active

in tests and gives us more confidence that DataMigration is using their

APIs as intended.



This sets up the fake testing implementations for the "Core" layer.

entry.title: [Passwords] Disable filling and saving for fields with not password predictions
entry.content:
This CL does the following:



- Don't consider fields with `NOT_PASSWORD`, `NOT_USERNAME`,

`ONE_TIME_CODE` in PwM heuristics. Disable saving/filling fallbacks.



`NOT_PASSWORD` and `NOT_USERNAME` predictions are overrides meaning

that these fields shouldn't trigger PwM. There is no practical use

to consider such fields in heuristics for a fallback after fields are

known to not be related to PwM.



This will also mean that heuristics to find username based on

interactability will ignore the interactability of the field with

`NOT_USERNAME` prediction. This is a heuristics behavior change.



- Don't consider fields with `CREDIT_CARD_VERIFICATION_CODE` and

`CREDIT_CARD_NUMBER` in PwM heuristics. Disable saving/filling

fallbacks.



Checked server predictions that have both

`CREDIT_CARD_VERIFICATION_CODE`/`CREDIT_CARD_NUMBER` and PwM

predictions: go/pwm-cvc-count

Low number suggests that users don't usually interact with PwM on

fields that were classified as CVC or CC number fields by Autofill. It

is safe to not propose PwM filling suggestions on such fields(even

without fallbacks).

entry.title: Use PlusAddressWebDataService in PlusAddressService
entry.content:
Currently, whenever plus addresses are polled from the backend, they are

simply persisted in PlusAddressService's members in memory. This is

implemented in PlusAddressService::UpdatePlusAddressMap().

This CL adds a round trip to the database to persist them there. For

now, this is completely unnecessary, since plus addresses are regularly

pulled from the backend anyways, including on start-up. However, once

the sync integration is done, PlusAddressService will solely rely on the

data from the database. In that sense, this CL adds the necessary

infrastructure and santiy checks that the database does work.



More specifically, this CL:

- Injects PlusAddressWebDataService into PlusAddressService via the

keyed service factory.

- Makes PlusAddressService a WebDataServiceConsumer, so it can receive

results from the database.

- Updates PlusAddressService::UpdatePlusAddressMap() to clear all

existing data from the database, insert all the new data received and

issue a read request for the data that was just inserted.

- Implements PlusAddressService::OnWebDataServiceRequestDone(), which is

called when the database read finishes. Updating PlusAddressService's

state is moved there.

- Issues a database read right after construction of PlusAddressService.

- Clear all data in the database on sign-out.

entry.title: AVFoundationCapture: forward sample timestamps under feature.
entry.content:
This CL introduces feature AVFoundationCaptureForwardSampleTimestamps

under which the AVFoundation capturer forwards sample timestamps in

the VideoFrameMetadata::capture_begin_time field.



The feature is default on. This should be safe since the sample

timestamps has been used since years. Had they not worked, downstream

WebRTC code would have had issues when trying to interpret the

resulting media::VideoFrame::timestamp() values.



The implication is that the TimestampAligner in [1] will be bypassed.

Since the epoch of the capture_begin_time and TimestampAligner is

the same, we eliminate estimation noise and should get sharper

timestamps to the other end.



[1] https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:third_party/blink/renderer/platform/peerconnection/webrtc_video_track_source.cc;l=241?q=webrtc_video_track_source.cc&ss=chromium

entry.title: jni_zero: Add option to use pickles to avoid re-parsing during registration generation
entry.content:
Chrome cannot use this option because GN has no way to add deps

onto the generate_jni() targets without also depending on their

associated compile targets (which would slow down the build by

synchronizing final dex and native link).



This model conceptually makes sense though, so I wanted to add

support for it. Doing so also simplifies the multiprocessing

portion of jni_registration_generator.py by restricting it to

only cover file parsing.



On my machine, timing of the the main chrome generation:

Before this change:

8.8s user 1.2s system 0.6 total

After this change:

8.5s user 1.2s system 0.8 total

After this change, using pickles:

0.4s user 0.0s system 0.4 total

entry.title: [ios] Improve build/toolchain/ios/swiftc.py script
entry.content:
Change the script build/toolchain/ios/swiftc.py to configure the

swift compiler to generate $input.swiftconstvalues files (needed

for Intents API in swift).



Improve the code to put all the derived data in one directory,

which allow removing the need for -pch-output-dir $dir from the

invocation of the script and its list of outputs (should avoid

the compilation error where $dir is created as a file instead of

a directory).

variables instead of command-line arguments (reduce the length of

the command-line and remove the need to parse those arguments in

the script).



Allow keeping the derived data dir between invocations of the

script (which may improve the build performance as the swiftc

binary will not have to rebuild the module cache each time).

entry.content:
With Graphite on Swiftshader, we use the GL fallback representation

which performs interop with the Graphite backing by reading from it and

uploading to a GL texture using glTexSubImage2D. However, it uses

glTexStorage2D if available when creating the texture which precludes

being able to redefine the texture with glTexSubImage2D. So simply use

glTexImage2D on creation which is fine since this is test-only code.

entry.title: [fuzztest] Use full optimization on engine parts
entry.content:
This ensures that fuzztest and centipede engine components are

optimized with -O2 even if the fuzz targets are configured to

compile with a lower optimization level (e.g. optimize_for_fuzzing

leading to -O1 or is_debug leading to -O0).



This leads to a faster and smaller engine in debug builds. It also

leads to fewer instrumented PCs in the engine parts which as

a side-effect also fixes the infinite loop in issue 326905381.



Tested locally with a V8 fuzztest target in release and debug with

asan.
